content:
Pull your data securely from Snowflake running on AWS into Data Manager using the Virtual Private Connection (VPC) for Snowflake connector for CRM Analytics. To use the CRM Analytics Snowflake VPC connector, you configure an outbound network connection, external credential, and named credential.

This feature is not generally available and is being piloted with certain Customers subject to additional terms and conditions. It is not part of your purchased Services. This feature is subject to change, may be discontinued with no notice at any time in Salesforce’s sole discretion, and Salesforce may never make this feature generally available.

You can’t use a custom authorization provider.
During the pilot, only username and password are supported for authenticating your Snowflake private connection.

Requires Salesforce Private Connect, which is provided by Salesforce as a courtesy for the duration of the pilot. You must configure your Snowflake for Private Link, to learn how to do this see the Snowflake guide AWS PrivateLink and Snowflake.

Allowlist the Salesforce AWS Account for Snowflake Private Connect
Determine the AWS region you’re running Snowflake Private Connect in. Get this value from the Region Field of SYSTEM$GET_PRIVATELINK_CONFIG in Snowflake.
From Setup, in the Quick Find box, enter Private, and then select Private Connect.
Open the AWS Region list and find your AWS account number.
Request your Snowflake admin add the account to the hostnames allowed list.

Create an Outbound Network Connection
From Snowflake determine your Amazon VPC endpoint service ID and AWS region from the VPC ID and Region fields of SYSTEM$GET_PRIVATELINK_CONFIG.
From Setup, in the Quick Find box, enter Private, and then select Private Connect.
Click Create Outbound Connection, select AWS PrivateLink, and click Next.
Give your connection a name.
For VPC Endpoint Service Name, enter com.amazonaws.vpce.<your AWS region>.vpce-svc-<your Amazon VPC endpoint service ID>.
For Region, select the AWS region you’re running Snowflake Private Connect in.
Select Yes, I would like to provision my connection now.
Save your outbound network connection.

Create a named credential
On the Named Credentials tab, click New.
Enter a label and name for your named credential.
For URL, enter https://<your Snowflake account name>.<your AWS region>.privatelink.snowflakecomputing.com.
Select the external credential and outbound network connection that you created.
Save your named credential.

Create a Snowflake VPC Connection
On the Data Manager Connections tab, click New Connection.
Select Private, then the Snowflake Private Connector, and click Next.
Enter the connector settings.
To validate your settings and test the connection, click Save & Test. If the connection fails, CRM Analytics shows possible reasons.

Exclude unnecessary or sensitive data from syncing to CRM Analytics with data sync filters. The filter runs on the source object and speeds up data sync by pulling only the data you need into CRM Analytics. If you expect to use excluded data in the future, use a recipe filter instead of a data sync filter to limit what’s written to a dataset.

You can only move data from Snowflake to CRM Analytics with this connector. It doesn't upload data from CRM Analytics to Snowflake.
Connected object names must start with a letter and contain only letters, digits, or underscores. An object name can’t end with an underscore.
The named credential must use the identity type Named Principal and have the status Authenticated.
title: Setting Up Snowflake VPC Connection in CRM Analytics
